%N A283971 a(n) = n except a(4*n + 2) = 2*n + 1.
%C A283971 From _Federico Provvedi_, Nov 13 2018: (Start)
%C A283971 For n > 1, a(n) is also the cycle length generated by the cycle lengths of the digital roots, in base n, of the powers of k, with k > 0.
%C A283971 Example for n=10 (decimal base): for every h >= 0, the digital roots of 2^h generate a periodic cycle {1,2,4,8,7,5} with period 6; 3^h generates {1,3,9,9,9,9,...} so the periodic cycle {9} has period 1; 4^h generates the periodic cycle {1,4,7} with period 3; etc. So, for n=10 (decimal base representation) the sequence generated by the periods of the digital roots of powers of k (with k > 0) is also periodic {1,6,1,3,6,1,3,2,1} with period 9, hence a(10) = 9. (End)
